{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658395"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20745"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11654"},{"type":"tags","id":"12441"},{"type":"tags","id":"12611"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EViral infections can cause various changes to host cells, leading to characteristic microscopic appearances.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic cytopathic effect of viral infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of polykaryons through cell fusion","Granulomatous inflammation","Calcification of necrotic tissue","Dense neutrophilic infiltration","Extensive fibrosis of affected tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of polykaryons through cell fusion\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a characteristic cytopathic effect seen in certain viral infections, particularly with measles virus and herpesviruses. Polykaryons are multinucleated giant cells that form when viruses cause the fusion of infected cells. This is a distinctive histological finding that helps in the diagnosis of specific viral infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDense neutrophilic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with acute bacterial infections rather than viral infections. Viral lesions are usually characterised by sparse inflammatory cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensive fibrosis of affected tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic response to tissue injury and is not a direct cytopathic effect of viral infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in infections with intracellular bacteria (like tuberculosis), fungi, or foreign body reactions, not as a primary viral cytopathic effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification of necrotic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is a late-stage response to tissue damage and not a direct viral cytopathic effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther characteristic viral cytopathic effects include the formation of inclusion bodies (as seen with herpesviruses or adenovirus), blister formation due to epithelial cell detachment, cellular proliferation (as in HPV-induced warts or molluscum contagiosum), and potential contribution to malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Viral infections can cause cytopathic effects including cell necrosis, cellular proliferation, and formation of inclusion bodies.","Some viruses induce cell fusion to form multinucleated cells called polykaryons.","Viral skin infections may manifest as blisters, proliferative lesions, or contribute to malignant neoplasms."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 348."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:36:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T21:45:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13621"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11654"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"General principles of microbial pathogenesis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}